sect2.para:
Sometimes patients may not have cognitive problems of their own, but they may be caregivers for someone with a neurocognitive disorder. In this case, the patient may not be in need of evaluation or treatment for cognitive problems per se, but they may be significantly affected by someone else’s cognitive disability. In this situation, the person who has the cognitive problems should be evaluated and treated, and the clinician should evaluate how the cognitive problems play a role in the patient’s presenting problems. Caring for someone with a cognitive disability can significantly and negatively impact a patient’s mental health (Segal et al.,
            2018
         ), and the burden of this may be a major focus of treatment.
